The term "consciousness" comes from the field of biopsychology and refers to the individual experience of being aware of one's environment, thoughts, and feelings. The condition of being aware of one's surroundings, as well as one's own thoughts and emotions, is referred to as consciousness. It is the personal experience of being aware of both oneself and the environment around oneself and others. The investigation of the neural correlates of consciousness, sometimes known as NCC for short, is the process of locating certain patterns of brain activity that are linked to the presence of conscious experience. Researchers in this subject are interested in figuring out which parts of the brain and mental processes are responsible for the creation of conscious experience. The study of consciousness makes use of a wide variety of experimental approaches, including as functional neuroimaging, electrophysiology, and lesion investigations, amongst others. Research on the function of the brain's default mode network (DMN) in consciousness is an example of a study that investigates the neural correlates of consciousness. The default mode network, also known as the DMN, is a network of brain areas that are active when a person is in a resting state, not focusing on the outer world, and introspecting, thinking about oneself as well as the past and the future. Studies have shown that the activity of the default mode network (DMN) has been discovered to have a positive correlation with the degree of awareness, and that the DMN is most active during self-referential thinking and mind-wandering. Researchers have also discovered that the activity of the DMN is lowered during the process of anesthesia, as well as in some brain illnesses, such as Alzheimer's disease, when there is an impairment of awareness. These results provide support for the hypothesis that the DMN is an important component of the neuronal processes underlying conscious experience. One such illustration of this would be the investigation of the function of the thalamus in relation to the conscious state. The thalamus is a structure that can be found in the brain, and its primary function is to act as a relay station for all of the sensory information that is received by the brain. Studies have shown that the thalamus plays a role in the control of one's level of consciousness and that the activity of the thalamus is connected to various states of consciousness. For instance, the activity of the thalamus slows down when one is in a deep sleep or when one is under some types of anesthesia. In a nutshell, the subjective experience of being aware of one's environment, thoughts, and feelings is what's meant when we talk about consciousness. The goal of the field of research known as the neural correlates of consciousness is to determine which parts and functions of the brain are responsible for the production of conscious experience. The investigation of consciousness makes use of a wide variety of experimental approaches, including as functional neuroimaging, electrophysiology, and lesion investigations, amongst others. According to the findings of several studies, the degree of consciousness is shown to have a positive correlation with the amount of activity in certain brain areas, such as the thalamus and the default mode network. 